    heroImage: '/images/categories/cichlid.jpg',
    productCount: 10,
    buyingGuide: '<p>With over 2,000 described species spread across Africa, Central and South America, and parts of Asia, cichlids represent one of the great success stories of vertebrate evolution. Their intelligence, complex social structures, and dazzling coloration have made them the cornerstone of the tropical fish hobby. Whether you are a seasoned breeder or just beginning to explore cichlid fish for sale, there is a species perfectly suited to your interests and experience.</p><h3>Why Cichlids Captivate Aquarists</h3><p>Unlike many tropical fish that serve as passive decoration, cichlids actively engage with their environment and their keepers. They recognise their owners, establish territories, perform elaborate courtship displays, and provide remarkable parental care — some species mouth-brood their fry, while others guard nests with aggressive determination. This behavioural richness means that a cichlid tank is never static. African Rift Lake cichlids from Lake Malawi and Lake Tanganyika offer electric blues, vivid yellows, and intricate patterns in a hard-water alkaline setup. South American cichlids — Oscars, Discus, Geophagus — tend toward softer, more acidic conditions and often display more nuanced, earthy coloration alongside dramatic personalities.</p><h3>Choosing the Right Cichlid</h3><p>The single most important decision when buying cichlids is matching species to your water chemistry and tank size. African Rift Lake cichlids require hard, alkaline water (pH 7.8-8.6) and do poorly in soft acidic conditions. Conversely, Discus and many South American species need soft, acidic water (pH 5.5-7.0) and high temperatures around 82-86 degrees Fahrenheit. Flowerhorn cichlids, a man-made hybrid, are best kept singly due to extreme aggression. When evaluating individual fish, look for vibrant coloration, erect fins, active swimming behaviour, and clear eyes. Avoid fish with clamped fins, faded colour, or visible white spots.</p><h3>Setting Up for Success</h3><p>Tank size varies widely by species — a pair of dwarf cichlids can thrive in 20 gallons, while a Flowerhorn needs 75 gallons minimum and a colony of Mbuna requires 55 gallons or more with extensive rockwork. Filtration should be robust, as cichlids are messy eaters that produce significant waste. Overstocking is a common strategy with African cichlids to diffuse aggression, but this demands powerful filtration and frequent water changes. Research compatibility carefully; many cichlid species will kill tankmates that intrude on their territory.</p><h3>The Fish Collection\'s Cichlid Collection</h3><p>We curate our cichlid offerings around quality over quantity. Each specimen is selected for colour intensity, body conformation, and genetic lineage. Our Flowerhorn collection features Kamfa and Super Red Dragon lines with documented parentage, while our African cichlids come from breeders who maintain wild-type genetics rather than diluted hybrid lines. Every fish ships with a species-specific care profile, and our team provides ongoing support to help you build and maintain a thriving cichlid community.</p>',
